<p><span><span><span><span><span><span>Humans and other primates, along with guinea pigs, cannot produce Vitamin C due to the <strong>lack of L-gulonolactone oxidase,</strong> an enzyme that is necessary to convert<strong> Glucuronate to L-gulonate in an NADPH-dependent reaction,</strong> which is necessary for <strong>production of ascorbic acid.</strong><br />
<br />
<em><strong>Reference:&nbsp;</strong>Harper&#39;s Illustrated Biochemistry, 31st Edition, Page no 195.</em></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<br />
&nbsp;

&nbsp;
<p><span><span><span><span><span><span>Some plants contain a deadly poison called fluoroacetate. Substances used for cancer treatment or as industrial chemicals, including pesticides, can turn into fluoroacetate in the body. It is poisonous because it binds to oxaloacetate and produces fluorocitrate, which stops a critical enzyme called aconitase from functioning properly, resulting in a build-up of citrate.<br />
<br />
<em><strong>Reference:&nbsp;</strong>Harper&#39;s Illustrated Biochemistry, 31st Edition, Page no 158.</em></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>
<br />
